---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Header from '../../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
import Icon from '../../components/Icon.astro';
import FinalCta from '../../components/FinalCta.astro';
import { postBySlug } from '../../data/posts';
import { site, waLink } from '../../data/site';

const post = postBySlug('top-5-iptv-boxes-uk-2026')!;
const canonical = `${site.url}/blog/${post.slug}/`;
const ogImage = post.image.startsWith('http') ? post.image : site.url + post.image;

const boxes = [
  {
    rank: 1,
    name: 'Formuler Z11 Pro Max',
    tagline: 'Purpose-built for IPTV, the box serious UK subscribers actually buy',
    priceBand: '£210 – £249',
    verdict: 9.6,
    bestFor: 'Portal and Xtream Codes users who want the most refined MYTVOnline experience available',
    resolution: '4K HDR10+',
    cpu: 'Quad-core Amlogic S905X4',
    ram: '4 GB DDR4',
    storage: '32 GB eMMC',
    os: 'Android 11 (Formuler skin)',
    apps: 'MYTVOnline 3, IPTV Smarters, TiviMate, OTT Navigator',
    pros: [
      'MYTVOnline 3 is the best dedicated IPTV portal app available on any hardware',
      'EPG, catch-up and multi-view (up to 4 simultaneous streams) all work without lag',
      'Wi-Fi 6 and Gigabit Ethernet, no buffering on 4K during peak hours',
      'Air-mouse remote included, a meaningful upgrade over any Fire Stick remote',
    ],
    cons: [
      'Higher upfront cost than a Fire Stick',
      'Not sold in UK high street stores, order from a Formuler reseller online',
    ],
    copy: `If you're looking for an IPTV box that UK households can use daily for several years without wanting to upgrade, the Formuler Z11 Pro Max is the one to buy. Formuler design their hardware around IPTV: MYTVOnline 3 handles Xtream Codes, M3U and Stalker portals natively, and it does so more smoothly than any competing portal app on any other platform. Sports, 4K HDR films, catch-up and series all load without the hesitation you get on cheaper Android boxes at the same price point. If your uk iptv subscription is portal-based (which most are), this is the box we'd put in a friend's living room.`,
  },
  {
    rank: 2,
    name: 'Amazon Fire TV Stick 4K Max (2nd gen)',
    tagline: 'Under £70, ships tomorrow and handles 4K IPTV without fuss',
    priceBand: '£59 – £69',
    verdict: 9.2,
    bestFor: 'Anyone starting a UK IPTV trial who wants the cheapest path to a working setup',
    resolution: '4K UHD, HDR10+, Dolby Vision',
    cpu: 'Quad-core 2.0 GHz',
    ram: '2 GB',
    storage: '16 GB',
    os: 'Fire OS 8 (Android based)',
    apps: 'IPTV Smarters Pro, TiviMate (sideload), Downloader, Kodi',
    pros: [
      'Inexpensive, small enough to take anywhere, available next-day from Amazon UK',
      'Wi-Fi 6E delivers stable 4K on any decent UK broadband connection',
      'Alexa voice remote makes finding channels faster than scrolling through a physical remote',
      'IPTV Smarters Pro sideloads via the Downloader app in under 5 minutes',
    ],
    cons: [
      '2 GB RAM means TiviMate with a heavy EPG can occasionally stutter',
      'Amazon shows promoted content on the home screen, pin IPTV Smarters to the front to avoid it',
    ],
    copy: `The Fire TV Stick 4K Max is why most first-time UK IPTV buyers never feel the need for a dedicated set-top box. It's under £70, plugs straight into any HDMI port, and IPTV Smarters Pro is running on it within a few minutes via the Downloader app. If you want to test an iptv subscription uk before deciding whether to invest in a Formuler, the Fire Stick 4K Max is the sensible hardware choice. It won't match a Formuler for portal polish, but for the vast majority of viewers it's the right answer to "what's the best value IPTV box in the UK right now?"`,
  },
  {
    rank: 3,
    name: 'Nvidia Shield TV Pro',
    tagline: 'The fastest Android TV box you can buy, with AI upscaling built in',
    priceBand: '£199 – £229',
    verdict: 9.1,
    bestFor: 'Sport enthusiasts and TiviMate users who want zero performance compromise on a large screen',
    resolution: '4K HDR, Dolby Vision, AI upscaling to 4K',
    cpu: 'Nvidia Tegra X1+ (256-core GPU)',
    ram: '3 GB',
    storage: '16 GB + microSD + USB expansion',
    os: 'Android TV 11',
    apps: 'TiviMate, IPTV Smarters, Kodi, Plex Server, Emby',
    pros: [
      'Fastest UI response of any streaming box, switching live channels during sport feels instant',
      'AI upscaling is genuinely useful when your IPTV subscription serves an HD or SD feed for a niche channel',
      'Also works as a Plex Media Server, useful for cord-cutters with existing media libraries',
      'Nvidia has issued security updates for Shield hardware for over 8 years, unusually long for consumer electronics',
    ],
    cons: [
      'Expensive relative to a Fire Stick for viewers who mainly watch standard content',
      'Nvidia has indicated a hardware refresh may be coming, some buyers prefer to wait',
    ],
    copy: `For anyone who watches UK sport seriously, the Shield TV Pro is the box that makes the investment make sense. TiviMate on a Shield is the benchmark for Android TV IPTV: the EPG is fast, channel switching is immediate, multi-view works without hesitation, and DVR recording to an attached USB drive is available natively. The AI upscaling is a practical benefit when a niche sport channel only serves 720p. It's overkill for casual viewers, but for the IPTV enthusiast it's the right tool.`,
  },
  {
    rank: 4,
    name: 'BuzzTV XR4500 / XPL 3000',
    tagline: 'A dedicated IPTV set-top box with a proper number-pad remote',
    priceBand: '£145 – £185',
    verdict: 8.6,
    bestFor: 'Buyers who want a Formuler-style experience with better UK stock availability',
    resolution: '4K UHD, HDR',
    cpu: 'Quad-core Amlogic S905X4',
    ram: '4 GB',
    storage: '32 GB',
    os: 'Android 10 (BuzzTV skin)',
    apps: 'BuzzTV Essentials, IPTV Smarters, TiviMate, OTT Navigator',
    pros: [
      'Built for IPTV from the ground up, portal loader is pre-installed, no sideloading needed',
      'Physical number-pad remote makes entering channel numbers fast, which older viewers appreciate',
      'Metal chassis runs cooler under load than any streaming stick',
      'Stocked by UK resellers with next-day delivery, which Formuler rarely matches',
    ],
    cons: [
      'App store is thinner than stock Android TV',
      'No Wi-Fi 6, use Ethernet for 4K to avoid any congestion issues',
    ],
    copy: `BuzzTV has become the go-to alternative to Formuler for UK buyers who can't find Z11 stock. The XR4500 is a proper set-top box (portal-first interface, number pad remote, HDMI-CEC) and it does the IPTV job well. If anyone in your household struggles with the swipe-heavy Fire Stick interface, BuzzTV's traditional TV-remote experience makes UK IPTV feel much more familiar from day one.`,
  },
  {
    rank: 5,
    name: 'MAG 524w3',
    tagline: 'The plug-in-and-watch portal box that\'s been in UK living rooms for a decade',
    priceBand: '£109 – £139',
    verdict: 8.3,
    bestFor: 'Subscribers whose provider gives them a MAG portal URL and who want zero setup complexity',
    resolution: '4K HDR',
    cpu: 'BCM75839 (Broadcom)',
    ram: '1 GB',
    storage: '4 GB',
    os: 'Linux (Infomir)',
    apps: 'Built-in Stalker portal (no third-party apps)',
    pros: [
      'Setup is: plug in HDMI and Ethernet, register the MAC address on the sticker, watch',
      'Linux-based, no Android overhead, near-instant startup from cold',
      'Wi-Fi 5 dual-band plus Ethernet port, suitable for most UK home network setups',
      'Remote is straightforward, no gesture navigation, no Alexa, just buttons',
    ],
    cons: [
      'Locked to portal streaming, Netflix, YouTube and other apps are not available',
      'Only relevant if your provider issues a MAG portal URL (UK IPTV BOX does)',
    ],
    copy: `MAG boxes have been the go-to for UK IPTV portal setups for years, and the 524w3 keeps that tradition going. If your iptv subscription uk comes with a portal URL rather than Xtream Codes credentials, a MAG box is the nearest equivalent to a traditional satellite receiver: plug in HDMI and Ethernet, register the MAC address on your provider's portal, and you're watching. No app store, no Android setup, nothing to configure. For viewers who want live UK TV, sport and films through a single clean interface without any extras, it's still a solid pick in 2026.`,
  },
];

const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'Which is the best IPTV box UK 2026?',
    a: 'For most UK households, the Amazon Fire TV Stick 4K Max is the best starting point. It\'s under £70, arrives next day and runs IPTV Smarters Pro without issue. If you want the most polished experience with an Xtream Codes or portal-based UK IPTV subscription, the Formuler Z11 Pro Max is what serious long-term users buy.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Is IPTV legal in the UK?',
    a: 'Using a fully licensed UK IPTV subscription that pays rights-holders for every channel it distributes is legal. Using services that stream Sky-exclusive or premium sport content without the correct licences is not. UK IPTV BOX is intended for lawful use of channels you\'re entitled to watch. Always verify the legality of any IPTV service in your jurisdiction before subscribing.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Can I test a service before I buy a box?',
    a: `Yes, that's the sensible order. For £${site.price} you can install IPTV Smarters on a phone, Smart TV, laptop or Fire Stick you already own and verify picture quality, EPG accuracy and channel selection before spending £200 on a Formuler. Test the service first, buy the hardware second.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'Formuler TV box vs Fire Stick: which should I buy?',
    a: 'Buy a Formuler if you watch IPTV daily, you use a portal or Xtream Codes subscription, and you want the most refined EPG, catch-up and multi-view on the market. Buy a Fire Stick 4K Max if you want the cheapest way to try iptv subscription uk first, you already use Amazon Prime or Netflix on the same TV, or you travel with your setup. Both work fully with UK IPTV BOX.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Do I need a VPN for IPTV in the UK?',
    a: 'No. A legal IPTV subscription doesn\'t require a VPN. Many UK viewers use one for general privacy or because their ISP throttles video traffic in the evening. If you do, choose one with reliable UK servers. NordVPN, Surfshark and Proton VPN are the most commonly reported to work well with IPTV in 2026.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What internet speed do I need for 4K IPTV?',
    a: 'Around 25 Mbps sustained for a single 4K stream, or 10 to 15 Mbps for HD. Households streaming two 4K channels at once should have at least 50 Mbps. Wired Ethernet always outperforms Wi-Fi for IPTV, even the best Wi-Fi 6 connection can drop frames during peak network congestion.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Will these boxes work with your IPTV UK trial?',
    a: 'Yes. Every box in this list works with UK IPTV BOX. Formuler, BuzzTV and MAG use portal or Xtream Codes credentials, which we send via WhatsApp. Fire Stick and Nvidia Shield users install IPTV Smarters Pro or TiviMate and log in with the same details. Full setup guides are linked at the bottom of this page.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How often should I replace my IPTV box?',
    a: 'A well-built box (Formuler, Shield, BuzzTV, MAG) typically lasts 4 to 6 years before it starts feeling slow. Fire Sticks tend to feel dated after 2 to 3 years as Amazon pushes heavier UI updates. If your box takes more than 5 seconds to switch channels or the EPG consistently lags behind the live signal, it\'s time to replace it.',
  },
];

const jsonLd = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@graph': [
    {
      '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
      itemListElement: [
        { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Home', item: `${site.url}/` },
        { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: 'Blog', item: `${site.url}/blog/` },
        { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 3, name: post.title, item: canonical },
      ],
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Article',
      headline: post.title,
      description: post.excerpt,
      image: ogImage,
      author: { '@type': 'Person', name: post.author, url: `${site.url}/about#team` },
      publisher: {
        '@type': 'Organization',
        name: site.name,
        url: site.url,
        logo: { '@type': 'ImageObject', url: `${site.url}/og-image.svg` },
      },
      datePublished: post.published,
      dateModified: post.updated,
      mainEntityOfPage: canonical,
      articleSection: 'IPTV Buying Guides',
      keywords: post.keywords.join(', '),
    },
    {
      '@type': 'ItemList',
      itemListOrder: 'https://schema.org/ItemListOrderDescending',
      name: post.title,
      numberOfItems: boxes.length,
      itemListElement: boxes.map((b) => ({
        '@type': 'ListItem',
        position: b.rank,
        name: b.name,
        description: b.tagline,
      })),
    },
    {
      '@type': 'FAQPage',
      mainEntity: faqs.map((f) => ({
        '@type': 'Question',
        name: f.q,
        acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: f.a },
      })),
    },
  ],
};

const relatedGuides = [
  { slug: 'enigma2-formuler', label: 'Set up IPTV on Formuler' },
  { slug: 'firestick', label: 'Set up IPTV on Fire Stick' },
  { slug: 'nvidia-shield', label: 'Set up IPTV on Nvidia Shield' },
  { slug: 'mag-box', label: 'Set up IPTV on MAG box' },
];

const publishedFmt = new Date(post.published).toLocaleDateString('en-GB', {
  day: 'numeric', month: 'long', year: 'numeric',
});
const updatedFmt = new Date(post.updated).toLocaleDateString('en-GB', {
  day: 'numeric', month: 'long', year: 'numeric',
});
---
<BaseLayout
  title={`${post.title} | ${site.name}`}
  description={post.excerpt}
  canonical={canonical}
  ogImage={ogImage}
  includeSchema={false}
>
  <Header />
  <main id="main">
    <!-- Hero -->
    <section class="relative overflow-hidden border-b border-border-subtle">
      <div class="pointer-events-none absolute inset-0 -z-10 opacity-70">
        <div class="absolute -top-40 left-1/2 h-[560px] w-[900px] -translate-x-1/2 rounded-full bg-grad-brand-soft blur-3xl"></div>
      </div>
      <div class="container-x pt-14 pb-12 md:pt-20 md:pb-16 max-w-3xl">
        <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb" class="text-xs uppercase tracking-widest text-text-muted">
          <a href="/" class="hover:text-brand-light">Home</a>
          <span class="mx-2 text-border-subtle">/</span>
          <a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-brand-light">Blog</a>
          <span class="mx-2 text-border-subtle">/</span>
          <span class="text-text-primary">IPTV Box UK 2026</span>
        </nav>

        <div class="mt-6 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3 text-xs uppercase tracking-widest text-text-muted">
          <span class="eyebrow">{post.category}</span>
          <span>· {post.readMinutes} min read</span>
          <span>· By {post.author}</span>
        </div>

        <h1 class="mt-6 font-display text-3xl md:text-5xl font-bold tracking-tight text-text-primary">
          Top 5 IPTV Boxes UK 2026: Ranked & Tested
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-5 text-lg text-text-muted leading-relaxed">
          The best IPTV box UK households can buy in 2026, ranked on 4K picture, EPG polish, app
          support and honest value. Every box below is paired with our <a href="/#pricing" class="text-brand-light underline underline-offset-4 decoration-brand/40 hover:decoration-brand-light">UK IPTV BOX UK IPTV subscription</a>
          so you can test the service before you spend on hardware.
        </p>

        <p class="mt-6 inline-flex items-center gap-2 text-xs uppercase tracking-widest text-text-muted">
          <span class="h-1.5 w-1.5 rounded-full bg-brand-light"></span>
          Published {publishedFmt} · Updated {updatedFmt}
        </p>

        <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
          <a href={waLink(`Hi, I read the Top 5 IPTV Boxes UK guide and would like to get the UK IPTV BOX subscription.`)} class="btn-primary" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">
            Get UK IPTV BOX Subscription
          </a>
          <a href="#comparison" class="btn-secondary">Jump to comparison</a>
        </div>

        <figure class="mt-10 overflow-hidden rounded-2xl border border-border-subtle bg-elevated/60">
          <img
            src={post.image}
            alt={post.imageAlt}
            width="1200"
            height="630"
            loading="eager"
            fetchpriority="high"
            decoding="async"
            class="w-full h-auto"
          />
        </figure>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Body -->
    <section class="container-x py-14 md:py-20 max-w-3xl is-visible" data-reveal="fade">
      <article class="legal-prose">

        <!-- Intro -->
        <p>
          Shopping for the best <strong>IPTV box UK</strong> viewers can actually buy in 2026? You're
          in the right place. We tested each of these boxes against a live <strong>UK IPTV subscription</strong>
          for two months (4K sport, HDR films, catch-up, series and multi-view) and ranked the five
          that came out ahead on picture quality, UI speed and reliability over a sustained period. If
          you're starting with <a href="/#pricing">UK IPTV BOX</a> to see whether the service suits
          your household before buying dedicated hardware, these are the boxes worth considering once
          you've made that decision.
        </p>

        <p>
          Short on time? Here's the ranking:
        </p>

        <ol>
          <li><a href="#formuler-z11-pro-max"><strong>Formuler Z11 Pro Max</strong></a>: best overall for portal and Xtream Codes UK IPTV</li>
          <li><a href="#fire-tv-stick-4k-max"><strong>Amazon Fire TV Stick 4K Max (2nd gen)</strong></a>: best value, the most popular UK pick</li>
          <li><a href="#nvidia-shield-tv-pro"><strong>Nvidia Shield TV Pro</strong></a>: most powerful, AI upscaling, best for 4K sport</li>
          <li><a href="#buzztv-xr4500"><strong>BuzzTV XR4500 / XPL 3000</strong></a>: dedicated IPTV set-top box with good UK stock</li>
          <li><a href="#mag-524w3"><strong>MAG 524w3</strong></a>: plug-in portal box, zero-configuration setup</li>

        </ol>

        <h2>How we ranked the best UK IPTV boxes for 2026</h2>
        <p>
          Five criteria, weighted to reflect what actually matters when you watch IPTV on a regular basis:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>4K playback stability (30%):</strong> dropped frames, buffer time on channel switch, HDR handling under load.</li>
          <li><strong>App and portal support (25%):</strong> TiviMate, IPTV Smarters Pro, MYTVOnline 3, Xtream Codes and M3U.</li>
          <li><strong>EPG speed and catch-up depth (15%):</strong> how quickly the guide loads and how far back the archive goes.</li>
          <li><strong>Build quality, remote and living-room usability (15%):</strong> whether a normal household actually enjoys using it.</li>
          <li><strong>Value for money (15%):</strong> measured against what a typical UK IPTV subscription costs.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Every box was tested with a real UK IPTV BOX line, not a demo feed, during a normal UK
          evening between 6 pm and 11 pm.
        </p>
      </article>

      <!-- Ranked cards -->
      <div class="mt-14 space-y-14">
        {boxes.map((b) => (
          <article
            id={
              b.rank === 1 ? 'formuler-z11-pro-max' :
              b.rank === 2 ? 'fire-tv-stick-4k-max' :
              b.rank === 3 ? 'nvidia-shield-tv-pro' :
              b.rank === 4 ? 'buzztv-xr4500' :
                             'mag-524w3'
            }
            class="card p-6 md:p-8 scroll-mt-24"
          >
            <div class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <span class="flex h-12 w-12 md:h-14 md:w-14 shrink-0 items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-grad-brand text-base md:text-lg font-bold !text-[#241056] shadow-glow">
                #{b.rank}
              </span>
              <div class="min-w-0">
                <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-brand-light">
                  Rated {b.verdict} / 10
                </p>
                <h2 class="mt-1 font-display text-2xl md:text-[28px] font-bold text-text-primary">
                  {b.name}
                </h2>
                <p class="mt-1 text-sm md:text-base text-text-muted">{b.tagline}</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <p class="mt-6 text-text-muted leading-relaxed">{b.copy}</p>

            <div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
              <div class="rounded-xl border border-border-subtle bg-elevated/50 p-4">
                <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-text-muted">Best for</p>
                <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-text-primary">{b.bestFor}</p>
              </div>
              <div class="rounded-xl border border-border-subtle bg-elevated/50 p-4">
                <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-text-muted">UK price band</p>
                <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-text-primary">{b.priceBand}</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <dl class="mt-6 grid gap-x-6 gap-y-3 sm:grid-cols-2 text-sm">
              <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 border-b border-border-subtle/60 pb-2">
                <dt class="text-text-muted">Resolution</dt><dd class="text-text-primary text-right">{b.resolution}</dd>
              </div>
              <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 border-b border-border-subtle/60 pb-2">
                <dt class="text-text-muted">CPU</dt><dd class="text-text-primary text-right">{b.cpu}</dd>
              </div>
              <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 border-b border-border-subtle/60 pb-2">
                <dt class="text-text-muted">RAM</dt><dd class="text-text-primary text-right">{b.ram}</dd>
              </div>
              <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 border-b border-border-subtle/60 pb-2">
                <dt class="text-text-muted">Storage</dt><dd class="text-text-primary text-right">{b.storage}</dd>
              </div>
              <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 border-b border-border-subtle/60 pb-2">
                <dt class="text-text-muted">OS</dt><dd class="text-text-primary text-right">{b.os}</dd>
              </div>
              <div class="flex justify-between gap-4 border-b border-border-subtle/60 pb-2 sm:col-span-2">
                <dt class="text-text-muted shrink-0">Best IPTV apps</dt><dd class="text-text-primary text-right">{b.apps}</dd>
              </div>
            </dl>

            <div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2">
              <div class="rounded-xl border border-brand/25 bg-brand/5 p-4">
                <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-brand-light">Pros</p>
                <ul class="mt-2 space-y-1.5 text-sm text-text-muted">
                  {b.pros.map((p) => (
                    <li class="flex gap-2">
                      <span class="mt-1 inline-flex h-4 w-4 shrink-0 items-center justify-center text-brand-light">
                        <Icon name="check" size={14} />
                      </span>
                      <span>{p}</span>
                    </li>
                  ))}
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div class="rounded-xl border border-border-subtle bg-elevated/50 p-4">
                <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest text-text-muted">Cons</p>
                <ul class="mt-2 space-y-1.5 text-sm text-text-muted">
                  {b.cons.map((c) => (
                    <li class="flex gap-2">
                      <span class="mt-1 inline-block h-1.5 w-1.5 shrink-0 rounded-full bg-text-muted"></span>
                      <span>{c}</span>
                    </li>
                  ))}
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="mt-6">
              <a
                href={waLink(`Hi, I'm interested in using the ${b.name} with UK IPTV BOX. Can you help me set it up?`)}
                class="btn-primary"
                target="_blank"
                rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer"
              >
                Get this box working with UK IPTV BOX
              </a>
            </div>
          </article>
        ))}
      </div>

      <!-- Comparison table -->
      <h2 id="comparison" class="mt-16 font-display text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary scroll-mt-24">
        IPTV box UK 2026: side-by-side comparison
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-text-muted">
        All five boxes at a glance. Prices are typical UK retail as of {updatedFmt}.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-6 overflow-x-auto rounded-2xl border border-border-subtle">
        <table class="w-full min-w-[720px] text-left text-sm">
          <thead class="bg-elevated/70 text-text-primary">
            <tr>
              <th class="p-3 font-semibold">Box</th>
              <th class="p-3 font-semibold">Resolution</th>
              <th class="p-3 font-semibold">RAM</th>
              <th class="p-3 font-semibold">Best app</th>
              <th class="p-3 font-semibold">Price</th>
              <th class="p-3 font-semibold">Score</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="text-text-muted">
            {boxes.map((b) => (
              <tr class="border-t border-border-subtle/60">
                <td class="p-3 text-text-primary font-medium">#{b.rank} {b.name}</td>
                <td class="p-3">{b.resolution}</td>
                <td class="p-3">{b.ram}</td>
                <td class="p-3">{b.apps.split(',')[0]}</td>
                <td class="p-3">{b.priceBand}</td>
                <td class="p-3 text-brand-light font-semibold">{b.verdict}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- Buyer's guide -->
      <article class="legal-prose mt-16">
        <h2>What to look for when buying a UK IPTV box</h2>
        <p>
          If you're new to IPTV hardware, here are the five specs that actually matter for a UK household:
        </p>

        <h3>1. Portal and Xtream Codes support</h3>
        <p>
          Most UK IPTV subscriptions today deliver via Xtream Codes (username, password, server URL)
          or a Stalker portal (MAC address). Formuler, BuzzTV and MAG boxes ship with portal loaders
          pre-installed, so there's no app to sideload. Fire Stick and Shield require installing IPTV
          Smarters or TiviMate separately, which takes about 5 minutes but isn't complicated.
        </p>

        <h3>2. 4K HDR handling</h3>
        <p>
          Any box you buy in 2026 should support 4K HDR10 at 60 fps as a minimum. Dolby Vision is
          a nice addition but rarely delivered on IPTV streams today. Be cautious of no-brand Android
          boxes that advertise 4K in the product title but downgrade to 1080p under real streaming load.
        </p>

        <h3>3. RAM and storage</h3>
        <p>
          2 GB RAM is the floor for a usable EPG. 4 GB is where TiviMate with multi-view and a full
          catch-up archive starts working without hesitation. Storage is less important because IPTV
          apps are small, but below 8 GB you'll run into update failures.
        </p>

        <h3>4. Wired Ethernet availability</h3>
        <p>
          The single most common cause of IPTV buffering complaints is Wi-Fi, not the subscription.
          Every box in our top five has a Gigabit or 100 Mbps Ethernet port. Use it. If cabling isn't
          an option, choose a box with Wi-Fi 6 and place it in the same room as your router.
        </p>

        <h3>5. Long-term software support</h3>
        <p>
          IPTV apps update regularly. A box that stops receiving Android OS updates within 12 months
          of purchase will eventually stop running the latest versions of Smarters or TiviMate. Formuler,
          Nvidia and Amazon have the most reliable update track records. Budget no-brand boxes are rarely
          worth the short-term price saving.
        </p>

        <h2>Test the service before you buy the hardware</h2>
        <p>
          The single most useful thing we tell buyers: <strong>verify the IPTV subscription first,
          then buy the box</strong>. A Formuler or BuzzTV costs £150 to £250. You can confirm that
          our channel line-up, 4K picture and EPG are what you want for
          <a href="/#pricing">£{site.price} on a 1-month plan</a>. Install IPTV Smarters on your
          phone, an existing Fire Stick or a laptop. If the service is what you hoped, invest in dedicated
          hardware. It's the lowest-risk order of operations.
        </p>

        <h2>Best IPTV app per box</h2>
        <p>
          Hardware is half the story. The app running on top determines the day-to-day experience:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Formuler Z11 Pro Max:</strong> MYTVOnline 3, pre-installed, the best portal app on any platform.</li>
          <li><strong>Fire TV Stick 4K Max:</strong> IPTV Smarters Pro via the Downloader app.</li>
          <li><strong>Nvidia Shield TV Pro:</strong> TiviMate. The Premium unlock is worth paying for.</li>
          <li><strong>BuzzTV XR4500:</strong> BuzzTV Essentials or IPTV Smarters Pro.</li>
          <li><strong>MAG 524w3:</strong> Built-in Infomir Stalker portal, no separate app required.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Full step-by-step setup guides for every device above are at our
          <a href="/installation-guides/">installation guides hub</a>.
        </p>

        <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
      </article>

